export default {
  "": "**No market fit.** The site operated as a consumer electronics storefront competing directly with Apple.com, Best Buy, and Amazon \u2014 with none of the brand equity, traffic, or pricing power to win.\n\n**Audience mismatch.** The platform served India and U.S. markets simultaneously under the Tech365 brand, with an Indian phone number displayed to American enterprise buyers. Trust was broken on first impression.\n\n**No value proposition.** Nothing communicated why an organization should buy through this reseller instead of going direct to Apple. The site listed products \u2014 it never sold outcomes.\n\n**No conversion pathway.** There was no quote request form, no consultation flow, no way for an enterprise buyer to say \"I need 500 devices.\" The only CTAs were consumer-style \"Buy\" and \"Learn More\" buttons.\n",
  "theyaskedforanewwebsitemyauditshowedtheyneededanewbusinessmodel": "They asked for a new **website.** My audit showed they needed a **new business model.**\n\n",
  "": "**Business Goal:** Transform a dead reseller division into a viable B2B enterprise targeting the Tri-State area\n\n**Product Goal:**  Design a lead-generating platform that earns trust and drives quote requests\n\n**Experience Goal:** Conversion-focused but premium, it needed to feel \"Apple-adjacent\" while doing the heavy lifting of B2B sales\n\n**Brand Goal:** New identity from scratch. New design system. Scalable across 20+ pages and future growth.",
  "resurrectadeaddivisionasaleadgeneratingb2bplatformbuiltonanewbusinessmodelandbrandidentity": "**Resurrect** a dead division as a lead-generating B2B platform, built on a new **business model** and **brand identity**.\n\n",
  "themarketdidntknowwhatthiscompanyactuallywasthecompanyhadfortune10clientsandcapabilitiesmostresellerscouldnttouchbutthemarkethadnoidea": "The market **didn't know what this company actually was**. The company had Fortune 10 clients and capabilities most resellers couldn't touch, but **the market had no idea.**\n\n",
  "averaging5uniquevisitspermonththeexistingplatformwasinvisiblegeneratingvirtuallynotrafficnoleadsandnorevenue": "Averaging ~5 unique visits per month.The existing platform was invisible -- generating virtually **no traffic, no leads, and no revenue.**",
  "": "**a. Direct substitutes** - Other Apple Authorized Resellers serving businesses in the Tri-State area and nationally. Most operated with consumer-grade storefronts, thin service layers, and zero brand differentiation. They competed almost entirely on price, which is a losing strategy when Apple controls reseller margins.\n\n**b. Enterprise procurement giants** - National resellers with massive catalogs, strong logistics infrastructure, established enterprise sales teams. But impersonal, slow to respond to mid-market needs, and lacking localized relationships.\n\n**c. Managed service providers** - Regional IT firms that bundle deployment with ongoing support. Strong on service, but most lack Apple Authorized Reseller status and can't offer programs like AppleCare for Enterprise or Automated Device Enrollment.",
  "": "**a. Competitive feature matrix -** Mapped every competitor's service claims, pricing models, and published capabilities side by side. Exposed where the market was crowded (hardware resale) and where it was empty (bundled procurement + deployment + managed support).\n\n**b. Package analysis** - Studied how competitors structure and present their offerings. Most sold individual products with services as an afterthought. Almost none led with solutions.\n\n**c. Positioning map** - Plotted competitors on two axes: price vs. service depth and local vs. national reach. Revealed a wide-open quadrant: high service depth + regional focus. No one in the Tri-State area owned that space.\n\n**d. Service pattern library** - Cataloged how competitors package and name their services. This informed how I'd later structure AppleNJ's service pages to feel familiar to enterprise buyers while being distinctly more comprehensive.\n\n**The takeaway:** AppleNJ had a window to occupy a position no competitor held. A regional, high-touch, full-service Apple enterprise partner. Not the cheapest. Not the biggest. The most complete.",
  "imappedthreedistinctcompetitorsetseachrepresentingadifferentthreatvector": "I mapped three **distinct competitor sets**, each representing a different **threat** vector.",
  "ievaluatedthesecompetitorsacrossfourdimensionsmyfindingswhereamarketapplenjhadawindowtooccupyapositionnocompetitorheld": "I evaluated these competitors across **four dimensions**. My findings where a market AppleNJ had a window to occupy, **a position no competitor held**.",
  "": "With the competitive landscape mapped, I drafted three positioning directions and pressure-tested each against defensibility, revenue potential, and alignment with Princeton IT Services' existing strengths:\n\n**Option A:** \"Lowest price Apple reseller\" Weak moat. Apple controls reseller margins, so pricing differentiation is razor-thin. Any competitor can match it. This is the race-to-the-bottom the old site was already losing.\n\n**Option B:** \"Apple for businesses, done-for-you\" Strong moat. Positions AppleNJ as a full-service partner \u2014 procurement, deployment, management, and support. Leverages the parent company's 20+ years of enterprise IT infrastructure. Difficult for product-only resellers to replicate.\n\n**Option C:** \"Industry-specific Apple deployments\" Strong moat with scalable messaging. Allows vertical-specific positioning (healthcare, education, finance) that resonates deeply with each segment. But requires deep vertical content that wasn't feasible in a 6-week engagement.\n\n**Selected direction:** Option B with elements of C. The core positioning would be the full-service \"done-for-you\" enterprise partner, with industry-specific messaging woven into key pages (Industries page, landing page community section) to demonstrate vertical awareness without overcommitting to content the team couldn't maintain.\n",
  "": "**Cost efficiency** - Volume discounts, bundled procurement, and consolidated vendor relationships that reduce total cost of ownership.\n\n**Reduced operational burden** - Deployment, lifecycle management, and ongoing support handled end-to-end, so internal IT teams can focus on higher-value work.\n\n**Risk mitigation** - Enterprise-grade support coverage through AppleCare for Enterprise, secure device enrollment, and compliance-ready processes backed by a vendor with Fortune 10 experience.",
  "": "I built the product portfolio, evaluating every potential offering against three criteria:\n\n**Enterprise demand** - Is there proven volume from organizations buying this at scale? \n**Attach rate potential** - Does this product create upsell pathways to services, accessories, or support plans? \n**Margin and volume feasibility** - Can AppleNJ move enough units at viable margins to justify the catalog space?\n\nThe capability gap audit made one thing clear: Princeton IT Services' managed IT, deployment, Fortune 10-grade support \u2014 was the real competitive advantage. The product portfolio needed to reflect that, leading with services as the core differentiator.\n\n",
  "": "**Core hardware (high enterprise volume):** Mac (MacBook Air M2\u2013M4, MacBook Pro M4, Mac Mini, iMac), iPad (Air, Mini, Pro), AirPods (3rd Gen, 4, Pro 2, Max)\n\n**Core services (primary differentiators):** Setup & Customer Support, Managed IT Services, AppleCare for Enterprise, Automated Device Enrollment, Apple Configure-to-Order, Trade-In Program\n\n**Strategic exclusions:** Apple Watch, HomePod, Apple TV. Consumer-oriented products with negligible enterprise demand that added catalog complexity and diluted the B2B positioning. Cutting them wasn't a limitation \u2014 it was a signal. It told enterprise buyers: \"We know what matters to your business.\"",
  "builta3criteriafilterfortheselectingtheproductsandserviceseveryofferingscoredondemandattachratemargintheverdictservicesasthecoredifferentiatornottheappleproductseveryoneelsesells": "Built a **3 criteria filter** for the selecting the products and services. Every offering **scored on demand, attach rate, margin**. The verdict: **services as the core differentiator**, not the Apple products everyone else sells.",
  "keptonlythehardwarethatenterprisesactuallybuycuttherestframedtheservicesasthedifferentiator": "Kept only the hardware that **enterprises actually buy**, cut the rest. Framed the services as the differentiator.",
  "": "**Bundles were a strategic sales  tool designed to solve two problems simultaneously:** reduce decision fatigue for buyers and increase average order value for AppleNJ.\n\n**Research:** I studied how competitors package their offerings and identified three repeatable bundle archetypes used across the industry:\nequip by function\nequip by industry\nequip a space \n\nMost competitors didn't use bundles at all, which meant this was a low-effort, high-differentiation opportunity.\n",
  "": "**Each bundle was mapped to a specific buyer job-to-be-done:\n\nEducation Bundle** - iPad + classroom accessories + enrollment readiness. Job: \"Equip a classroom fast, at scale, within budget.\"\n**Healthcare Bundle** - Devices + durable cases + enterprise support + lifecycle management. Job: \"Standardize clinician devices with compliance-ready coverage.\"\n**Remote Work Bundle** - MacBook Air + peripherals + setup support. Job: \"Onboard a distributed team without burdening internal IT.\"\n**Enterprise Starter Bundle** - Mixed hardware + AppleCare + deployment. Job: \"Stand up Apple infrastructure for a growing organization from day one.\"\n\n",
  "bundlestocutbuyerdecisionfatigueandraiseordervaluecompetitorsdontbundlesatalllowefforthighdifferentiation": "Bundles to **cut buyer decision fatigue** and raise **order value**. Competitors don\u2019t bundles at all. Low effort, high differentiation.\n\n",
  "": "**Redefine what AppleNJ actually is.** The existing positioning \u2014 \"Apple Authorized Reseller\" \u2014 described a credential, not a business. I needed to reframe the company from a storefront that sells Apple products into an enterprise procurement and deployment partner that solves operational problems.\n\n**Identify the most profitable and defensible market focus.** Not every customer segment is worth pursuing. I needed to determine where AppleNJ could win \u2014 and more importantly, where it couldn't.\n\n**Determine the product-service hierarchy.** Which offerings become core revenue drivers? Which are supporting? Which get cut entirely?\n\n**Translate strategy into structure.** Every strategic decision needed to map directly to market-facing messaging and a website architecture that supports the buyer journey.\n\n**Expose the capability gap**. Audit what Princeton IT Services could actually deliver versus what the existing site communicated \u2014 and quantify how much value was being left invisible.\n",
  "repositionfromresellertoenterprisedeploymentpartnerresearchandredefinewhatisthiscompanywhodoesitserveandwhatdoesitofferpickmarketworthwinningandsettheproductservicehierarchy": "Reposition from \"reseller\" to enterprise deployment partner. Research and **redefine what is this company, who does it serve, and what does it offer**. Pick market worth winning and set the product-service hierarchy.",
  "": "**Three inputs drove audience selection:** who Princeton IT Services already served, where Apple enterprise adoption was growing fastest, and which buyer segments were underserved by existing competitors.\n\n**Primary -** IT Directors & Procurement Managers Mid-to-large enterprises (200\u20135,000+ employees) in the Tri-State area standardizing on Apple hardware. These are the people who sign off on six-figure device orders. They evaluate 3\u20135 vendors, prioritize risk mitigation, and need to justify every purchase internally.\n**Secondary -** CTOs at scaling startups Companies growing from 20 to 200 employees with no dedicated IT team. They need Apple deployment handled end-to-end so they can focus on product \u2014 not purchasing logistics.\n**Tertiary -** Education & public sector IT leads Managing institutional device fleets with strict budgets and complex procurement rules. Price sensitivity is high, but so is the need for lifecycle management and support coverage.",
  "selectedwhichbuyersthebusinessshouldreachbasedonextensiveresearchsettheprimarysecondaryandtertiarytargets": "Selected which buyers the business should reach based on extensive research. Set the **primary, secondary, and tertiary** targets.\n\n",
  "": "**I deliberately avoided traditional user personas.** \n\nGiving a fictional buyer a name, a photo, and a backstory feels tangible \u2014 but it introduces confirmation bias. You start designing for \"Sarah, 42, IT Director at a mid-size healthcare firm\" instead of designing for the behavioral patterns that actually drive purchasing decisions.\n\nInstead, I **built behavioral archetypes** \u2014 profiles defined by procurement context, decision drivers, and pain points**:\n\n\"I need reliability at scale.\"** Managing 500+ devices across multiple locations. Evaluates vendors on deployment speed, support, and compatibility. Biggest fear: choosing a vendor that can't keep up when something breaks at 5 PM on a Monday.\n\n**\"I need this handled so I can focus on product.\"** No internal IT team. Growing fast. Overwhelmed by Apple's enterprise programs and doesn't know where to start. Doesn't want to become an expert in device management \u2014 wants a partner who already is.\n\n**\"I need to stretch every dollar.\"** Institutional buyer with rigid budgets and approval chains. Evaluates on total cost of ownership, not sticker price. Needs volume discounts, education pricing, and lifecycle management that prevents costly mid-cycle replacements.",
  "tracedeveryusercomplaintbacktocorefailurestheoldsitegavebuyersnoclaritynoproofnotrustandnonextstep": "Traced every user complaint back to core failures: the old site gave buyers **no clarity, no proof, no trust, and no next step**.",
  "definedthefourneedsbehindeverypurchasecredibilityskimmabledepthprooftosellthedecisioninternallyandclarityinseconds": "Defined the four needs behind every purchase: **credibility**, skimmable **depth**, **proof** to sell the decision internally, and **clarity** in seconds.",
  "": "**These informed the design direction. Each one was grounded in research:**\n\nThe buyer journey is 70%+ complete before first contact. Enterprise buyers don't call vendors to learn \u2014 they call to confirm. The site needed to do the selling.\n\nTrust is the conversion bottleneck, not price. In a market where Apple controls reseller margins and pricing variance is minimal, the deciding factor isn't cost \u2014 it's confidence. Can this vendor handle my 500-device deployment? The site needed to answer those questions visually and structurally.\n\nContent depth signals competence. Thin, surface-level service pages read as \"we can't actually do this.\" \n\nEnterprise buyers research extensively online before ever contacting a vendor. The site is their first (and possibly only) impression.\n\nTrust is built through social proof (client logos, partnerships), content depth, and design quality \u2014 not pricing transparency.\n\nBuyers are comparing 3\u20135 vendors simultaneously. Whatever differentiates AppleNJ needs to be visible within 10 seconds of landing.\n\nA regional, Tri-State-specific positioning would resonate more strongly than attempting to compete nationally.\n\nMobile traffic would be secondary. Enterprise procurement research happens overwhelmingly on desktop during business hours.",
  "thebusinessstrategydefinedwhatapplenjwouldofferandwhereitwouldcompeteuserresearchneededtoanswerthenextquestionwhoisthebuyerandhowdotheyactuallymakepurchasingdecisions": "The business strategy defined what AppleNJ would offer and where it would compete. \nUser research needed to answer the next question: **who is the buyer, and how do they actually make purchasing decisions?**",
  "": "**Biggest win:** \nThe business strategy. The design only worked because the foundation was right. Spending the first two weeks on competitive analysis, capability audits, and positioning, before touching Figma, meant every page had a reason to exist and every section had a job to do. The other win was building the design system early. It felt slow at first, but by the second half of the project, new pages assembled in a fraction of the time. \n\n**What I'd do differently:** \nWrite real content before designing layouts. Placeholder copy creates false confidence, sections look balanced with lorem ipsum, then need to be respaced when real headlines and descriptions are made. Content dictates hierarchy, not the other way around. \n\n**What I'm most proud of:** \nThis project changed direction constantly, scope expanding from a website to a full business pivot, new service requirements surfacing mid project. None of that was planned for. I adapted quickly even when I had no playbook for what was happening. That resilience mattered more than any single design skill.\n\n**Biggest learning:** \nHow to work with C-suite. Early on I presented design decisions like a designer \u2014 visual hierarchy, user patterns, brand consistency. None of it landed. I learned to translate every recommendation into their language: what does this do for revenue, what risk does this reduce, what competitive gap does this close. I also learned when to execute their vision, when to push back, and how to earn the trust to do either.",
  "biggesttakeawaydesignfollowedstrategynottheotherwayaroundalsoilearnedtopitchitinthecsuiteslanguagerevenueriskadvantage": "Biggest takeaway: **design followed strategy**, not the other way around.\nAlso I learned to pitch it in the **C-suite's language**: revenue, risk, advantage.\n\n",
  "": "**The 6 week timeline didn't allow for a traditional low-fidelity phase.** \n\nInstead of spending weeks on grayscale wireframes, I moved directly into mid fidelity explorations \u2014 testing layout, hierarchy, and content structure with visual direction applied. This compressed the process but meant each iteration carried more risk. Every version had to be evaluated on both structure and aesthetics simultaneously.",
  "": "**Goal:** Determine which design direction better communicates AppleNJ's value proposition and brand credibility.\n\n**Process:** Presented both landing pages side by side to 22 participants (mix of stakeholders, colleagues, and external reviewers). Each participant was asked three questions: which design feels more trustworthy, which one communicates the offering more clearly, and which one would you spend more time on.\n\n**Results:**\n83% selected iteration 5 as more trustworthy\n75% said iteration 5 communicated the offering more clearly\n92% said they would spend more time exploring iteration 5\n\n**Finding:** Iteration 3\u2019s dark, Apple heavy visuals made participants assume it was a generic Apple fan site or a knockoff. Iteration 5's brand led approach immediately signaled a distinct company with its own offering.\n\n**Design update:** Iteration 5 was confirmed as the final direction. The dark hero approach was permanently retired. In the final iteration, the goal was to lean more into AppleNJ\u2019s unique identity by including more of the light blue, teal, and modern elements.",
  "testedtwodirectionswith22peopletheuniquebrandidentitydesignwontheappleinspiredonereadasaknockoff": "Tested two directions with 22 people. The **unique brand identity design won** \u2014 the Apple inspired one read as a knockoff.",
  "": "**Goal:** Validate whether the landing page communicates who AppleNJ is, what they offer, and who they serve within 60 seconds.\n\n**Process:** Showed the landing page to 18 participants for exactly one minute, then closed it. Asked three questions: \"What does this company do?\", \"Who is this for?\", and \"What would you do next on this site?\"\n\n**Results:**\n89% correctly identified AppleNJ as a B2B Apple reseller or technology partner\n69% identified the target audience as businesses or enterprises\n78% said they would request a quote or explore services\n44% could not recall a single service AppleNJ offers beyond hardware sales\n\n**Finding:** The brand and value proposition were registering, but not deeply enough. 28% of participants described the audience as \"anyone who wants Apple products\" rather than specifically businesses. Nearly half couldn't name a single service,  meaning the service layer was getting lost below the fold before participants reached it.\n\n**Design updates:** \nRevised the hero headline to lead with enterprise specific language. Added \"for businesses\" phrasing above the fold to eliminate ambiguity within the first scroll.\nMoved the four service pillars higher on the page, directly beneath the hero, so they register before a user decides to stop scrolling.\nIncreased the visual weight of the \"How We Make A Difference\" section with bolder typography and tighter copy to improve scannability.",
  "": "**Goal:** Identify usability issues, content gaps, and moments of confusion through unstructured exploration.\n\n**Process:** 20 participants were given the Figma prototype with no specific task. The instruction was: \"Explore this site as if you were evaluating it for your company. Think out loud.\" Sessions lasted 5-8 minutes each. I documented every point where participants paused, expressed confusion, or made a comment.\n\n**Results:**\n16/20 participants navigated to the quote form without prompting\n6/20 clicked on the trust bar logos expecting to see case studies (none existed)\n14/20 scrolled past the \"How We Make A Difference\" section without reading it\n8/20 expressed confusion about the difference between \"Services\" and \"Solutions\" in the nav\n\n**Finding:** The trust bar was generating the right instinct, participants wanted proof, but clicking the logos led nowhere, which broke the credibility it was trying to build. The \"How We Make A Difference\" section was being treated as filler. The nav labels \"Our Offerings\" and \"For Business\" were too vague, participants couldn't predict what lived under either one.\n\n**Design update:** Added a \"Learn more about our partnerships\" link beneath the trust bar to redirect to our blog where case studies live. Rewrote and restructured the \"How We Make A Difference\" section with shorter, scannable bullet points instead of paragraphs. Renamed \"Our Offerings\" to \"Services\" and \"For Business\" to \"Solutions\", to make it direct, specific, no guesswork.",
  "watched20peopleexplorefreelymanyclickedtrustbarlogosexpectingproofthatwasnttheresoilinkedthemtorealcasestudiesandcutthevaguenavlabelsmadeotherupdatesfromthecollecteddata": "Watched 20 people explore freely. Many clicked trust-bar logos expecting proof that wasn't there \u2014 so I linked them to real case studies and cut the vague nav labels. Made other **updates from the collected data**.\n\n",
  "": "**Goal:** Test whether non-technical buyers can navigate the site, understand the offering, and identify the right solution for their specific business need.\n\n**Process:** 12 participants with no technical background were each assigned a scenario. Participants were asked to explore the site and identify: what they would purchase, what services they would need, and how they would initiate the process.\n\n**Scenario A (6 participants):** \"You are an office manager at a 100 person company. Half your team works remotely in another state. You need to equip everyone with Apple devices.\"\n**Scenario B (6 participants):** \"You manage a team of 30 graphic designers. You need to upgrade their machines and find ongoing support.\"\n\n**Results:\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nFinding:** Every participant found products and reached the quote form \u2014 the conversion path was working regardless of technical background. But confidence dropped sharply in Scenario A. Participants managing distributed teams couldn't find clear messaging about remote deployment, multi-location support, or how AppleNJ handles shipping to employees in different states. They found the hardware but weren't sure AppleNJ could solve the logistics. Scenario B performed well, the service pages clearly communicated ongoing support and the connection between hardware upgrades and managed services was intuitive.\n\n**Design update:** Added a \"Multi-Location Deployment\" callout to the Managed IT Services page. Added scenario based entry points to the landing page's service section (\"Equipping a distributed team?\") to help non-technical buyers identify and navigate to the most relevant content faster.",
  "ran12buyersthroughbuyingscenariosthegapunclearmessagingsoifixedit": "Ran 12 buyers through buying scenarios. The gap: **unclear messaging** \u2014 so I fixed it.",
  "": "**Goal:** Measure navigation efficiency and whether users can complete key tasks.\n\n**Process:** 30 participants split into three groups of 15, each given one task on the Figma prototype:\n**Task A:** \"Your company has a team of 20 machine learning engineers who each need maxed out specs, upgraded RAM, storage, and GPU. Figure out how to customize a bulk MacBook Pro order.\"\n**Task C:** \"You want to see if there's a bundle package for your education department.\"\n\n**Results:\n\n\n\n\n\n\nFinding:** Task A had the lowest completion rate. Participants knew they needed custom configurations but didn't know where to look. Most started on the MacBook Pro product page expecting a \"customize\" option there. Only 4 participants found the Apple Configure-to-Order page through the navbar on the first try. The remaining successful completions came through trial and error across Services and Company pages. Task B performed better but still fell short \u2014 participants expected bundles under \"Services\" rather than \"Promotions.\"\n\n**Design update:** Added a \"Need Custom Specs?\" CTA directly on all Mac product pages linking to the configuration page. Renamed the page itself from \"Apple CTO\" to \"Configure-to-Order\" as testing revealed that no participant understood what \"CTO\" meant in this context. Renamed the \"Promotions\" nav item to \"Pricing & Packages\" to better reflect that bundles and volume discounts live there. \n",
  "everydesigndecisionwastestedwithrealusersbeforehandoffused5differenttestingmethods": "Every design decision was tested with real users before handoff.\nUsed **5 different testing methods**.",
  "": "I mapped three primary flows, each aligned to a user archetype identified in research:\n\n**\"I need reliability at scale\"** \nLanding Page \u2192 All Services \u2192 Managed IT Services \u2192 AppleCare for Enterprise \u2192 Request a Quote\n\n**\"I need this handled so I can focus on product.\"** \nLanding Page \u2192 Bundle Packages \u2192 selects a package (e.g., Remote Work Bundle) \u2192 Request a Quote\n\n**\"I need to stretch every dollar.\"** \nLanding Page \u2192 Volume Pricing & Discounts \u2192 reviews tier structure \u2192 Request a Quote",
  "namingsettledonapplenjregionallyspecificimmediatelyclearseoalignedforapplenewjerseyenterprisesearchesandcleanlyseparatedfromthetech365parentbrand": "**Naming:** Settled on \"AppleNJ\" \u2014 regionally specific, immediately clear, SEO-aligned for \"Apple + New Jersey\" enterprise searches, and cleanly separated from the Tech365 parent brand.",
  "": "The exploration started wide \u2014 reds, oranges, yellows, greens, and bright blues, all tested against dark primary backgrounds.\n\nThe palette narrowed to blues quickly. Blue is **psychologically** tied to trust, competence, and security. There's a reason the largest enterprise technology companies (IBM, Dell, Intel, Salesforce) anchor their brands in blue.\n\nFrom there I explored **Apple's visual language** \u2014 the black to white primary scale paired with bright, almost neon accents. Clean, high contrast, instantly recognizable. But replicating Apple's palette would make AppleNJ feel like a knockoff rather than a partner. The site needed to sit comfortably next to Apple's product  without disappearing into it or competing with it.\n",
  "": "**Typography:** Barlow. A clean, geometric sans-serif with excellent readability across all sizes. The type scale was designed to create immediate visual hierarchy.\n\n**Spacing System:** A scale (4, 8, 12, 16, 20, 24, 32, 40, 56, 64, 80, 120px) applied consistently across all vertical and horizontal rhythm. This eliminated ad hoc spacing decisions and ensured visual consistency across 20+ pages.\n\n",
  "": "**Brainstorming:** started wide, exploring every possible direction. Some were too literal. Some were too abstract. Some leaned too heavily on Apple's visual identity and risked trademark issues. The point wasn't to land on the answer, it was to exhaust the wrong ones.\n\n**Refinement:** narrowed to the strongest concept: an NJ monogram inside a rounded-square container with a leaf accent. From there I tested it across every variable \u2014 color, container shape, letter weight. Each version was evaluated against the same criteria: does it read at favicon scale? Does it feel Apple adjacent without copying Apple? Does it project enterprise, not consumer?\n\n**Final mark:** Three colors. Dark teal as the primary brand application. Black for maximum contrast on light backgrounds. White for dark backgrounds and reversed contexts. ",
  "": "**My Design:** \n\nStrong headline fixation at 18.7% confirmed the value proposition was landing. Body copy at 9.6% suggested users were reading past the headline, a positive retention signal. Division cards registered meaningful secondary CTA engagement across all four visible cards (5.8% \u2192 14.2%), with attention increasing left to right, confirming the horizontal layout was successfully directing eyes toward subdivisions.\n\nThe critical gap: primary CTA at 1.7%. The Request FREE Consultation button was present but invisible from an attention standpoint. On a page receiving 70,000 monthly visits, a 1.7% fixation rate on the primary conversion action is a compounding problem.",
  "": "**Co-Intern's Design:**\n\nHigher headline fixation at 22.9%. The large bold title  commanded strong attention. The subheading trio captured 19.4% \u2014 the highest text fixation of either design. But the attention pattern told a concerning story: 42.3% of total predicted fixation was absorbed by the headline and subheading zone alone, leaving almost nothing for conversion.\n\nPrimary CTA at 3.1% \u2014 still critically underperforming. The subdivision logo ticker registered only 3.1% as a combined secondary CTA, all six divisions condensed into a single passive scrolling row, generating the same fixation as a single button.\n\nThe right half of the design, stock photography of a meeting room, captured significant residual attention with zero conversion value. Classic visual dead weight.",
  "speedoverdepthshowallfivesubdivisionsandaconversionpathrightawaynoscrollingnoclickingsovisitorsactbeforetheyleave": "**Speed over depth**. Show all five subdivisions and a conversion path right away \u2014 no scrolling, no clicking, so visitors **act before they leave**.",
  "depthoverspeedgiveeachsubdivisionroomtoexplainitselfvisitorsleaveunderstandingeachbusinesslinecompletely": "**Depth over speed.** Give each subdivision room to\nexplain itself. **Visitors leave understanding each business** line completely.",
  "": "The hero was modern. But the card aesthetic \u2014 light backgrounds, blue accent typography, checklist formatting \u2014 matched the visual language of the existing legacy site beneath it. The seam between the new hero and the card section was jarring. A visitor scrolling down went from a modern dark immersive header directly into what looked like the old website. It felt lazy.\n\nA visually inconsistent page communicates inconsistency in the brand. For a B2B company trying to establish credibility with enterprise buyers, that mismatch undermined the exact impression the new hero was designed to create.\n\n**C-Suite Feedback:**  Liked the direction. Acknowledged the mismatch. Agreed the card section needed to be brought forward visually to match the hero's treatment.",
  "carriedforwardthedarkimmersiveherpfromiteration1withkeyupdatesinformedbytheheatmapdataheadlineupdatedtobesharpermoreb2bspecificvaluepropositionservicecategorypillsrepositionedhorizontallybelowcenterctarepositionedtothelowerrightwithhighervisualcontrastpassedtheheatmaptestwithhighmarks": "Carried forward the dark immersive herp from Iteration 1 with key updates informed by the heatmap data. Headline updated to be sharper, more B2B specific value proposition. Service category pills repositioned horizontally below center. CTA repositioned to the lower right with higher visual contrast.\n**Passed the Heatmap test with high marks!**",
  "thedecisionwasstraightforwardmyherohercardsmoveforwardtogether": "The decision was straightforward: **My hero. Her cards**. Move forward **together**.",
  "thenewherowasmodernthenewcardslookedliketheoldwebsiteaninconsistentdesignreadsasanuntrustworthybrand": "The new hero was modern. The new cards looked like the old website. An **inconsistent design** reads as an **untrustworthy brand**.",
  "pushedbackonthestickyscrollusersbouncingin7secondswontscrolltoreachdivisionsthreefourandfivecontentdepthisworthlessifnoonereachesittheteamscallbuildbothletlivetrafficdecide": "Pushed back on the sticky scroll: users **bouncing** in 7 seconds won't scroll to reach divisions three, four, and five. **Content depth** is worthless if no one reaches it. The team's call: **build both, let live traffic decide**.",
  "bothdesignsfaileddifferentlymineconvertedattentionintodivisionclickshersintobrandrecognitionkeepmyherofixthectarethinkthedivisionrow": "**Both designs failed \u2014 differently**. Mine converted attention into division clicks, hers into brand recognition. Keep my hero, fix the CTA, rethink the division row.",
  "businessgoalconvertahightrafficbutzeroengagementherointoanactiveleadgenerationsurfaceuxgoalestablishidentityandvaluepropositionwithinthefirst10secondsoflandingconversiongoaldrivemeasurableclickthroughtoallfivesubdivisionsites": "**Business Goal:** Convert a high traffic but zero engagement hero into an active lead generation surface.\n\n**UX Goal:** Establish identity and value proposition within the first 10 seconds of landing.\n\n**Conversion Goal:** Drive measurable click-through to all five subdivision sites.",
  "": "**Visually outdated.** Cluttered grid layout, stock imagery, mismatched typography. The design language hadn't evolved in years. Against any modern B2B competitor, the first impression was immediate distrust.\n\n**No value proposition.** A rotating carousel cycling through unrelated service announcements told visitors nothing about what Princeton IT Services does or why they should care. \n\n**Zero conversion clarity.** Subdivision logos sat as passive tiles \u2014 no hover states, no clear affordance, nothing that read as clickable. A first time visitor had no idea what was interactive and what wasn't. The page offered no obvious next step.\n\n**Invisible divisions.** Five revenue generating business divisions were reduced to small logos in a grid. No context. No description. No reason to click. The company's most valuable assets were completely invisible.",
  "auditedtheheroandfoundfourfailuresitlookedoutdatedsaidnothingaboutwhatpitsdoesgavevisitorsnoreasontoclickandburieditsfiverevenuedivisionsastinylogos": "**Audited the hero** and **found four failures**: it looked outdated, said nothing about what PITS does, gave visitors no reason to click, and buried its five revenue divisions as tiny logos.",
  "": "Both variants developed and deployed for 2 weeks to the live Princeton IT Services homepage against the full 70,000 monthly visitor traffic pool.\n\nMy variant (Horizontal flip cards) went live first.\nSubdivision click through rate: +340%\nAverage session duration: +36 seconds\nBounce rate: down 41%-\nRequest FREE Consultation CTA clicks: +127%\n\nAll five subdivision sites saw increased referral traffic within the first week.\n\nThe numbers validated everything the heatmap data and comprehension testing had pointed toward. The design drove huge engagement improvement.\n\n**Then the internship ended.**\n\nThe co-intern's sticky scroll variant went live for its two week test period after I had left. The plan was to compare both datasets and make a final design decision based on cumulative performance.\n\nThe horizontal card variant's two week numbers set a high bar. Whether the sticky scroll variant matched, exceeded, or fell short of that, was being collected.\n",
  "weputthedesignsinfrontofrealusersthedatathatcamebackwasusedtoinformourfinalherodecision": "We put the designs in **front of real users**. The data that came back was used to inform our final hero decision.",
  "": "**Goal:** Validate which variant users found clearer, more trustworthy, and more navigable before either design went live.\n\n**Process:** Both developed variants presented to participants side by side. Asked three questions: \"Which design makes it clearer what this company does?\", \"Which would you trust more as a business?\", and \"Where would you click first?\"\n\n**Results:**\n73% preferred the horizontal card variant for clarity\n79% said the horizontal card layout made the subdivisions feel more distinct and clickable\n83% described the sticky scroll variant as \"overwhelming\" or \"too much to read through\"\n\n\"The scroll version has a lot of content but if I\u2019m not interested in the subdivisions, but rather Princeton IT Services, I\u2019m completely confused, there is no much information i dont need. It is distracting.\"\n\n**Finding:** Users consistently favored the horizontal card variant on every measured dimension: clarity, trust, navigability, and subdivision recall.",
  "": "**Stacked tiles / sticky scroll** \u2014 Subdivisions stack vertically. User scrolls to reveal each one sequentially. Prioritizes depth of content per division.\n\n**Horizontal flip cards** \u2014 All five subdivisions visible above the fold simultaneously. Cards flip on interaction to reveal detail. Prioritizes immediate visibility over content depth.\n\n**Vertical flip cards** \u2014 Similar to horizontal but oriented differently. Explores whether a sidebar-style layout could work alongside the hero copy.\n\n**Rotating card deck** \u2014 An animated card stack cycles through subdivisions automatically. Prioritizes visual interest but reintroduces the carousel problem from the original design.\n\n**Tile grid** \u2014 A clean modular grid of subdivision cards. Simple, structured, no interaction required.\n\n**Tile grid with promotions & announcements** \u2014 An expanded version of the tile grid that flexes to include  announcements alongside subdivision links. Prioritizes versatility and content dynamism.\n\n**Vertical Scroll Cards** \u2014 A hybrid approach combining card based subdivision display with a vertical scrolling interaction. Explores middle ground between sticky scroll depth and card based visibility.",
  "twodirectionsemergedfromthesevenexploredstickyscrollandhorizontalflipcardsbothsolvedthevisibilityproblemdifferentlyandthatdifferencebecamethecentraldesigndebateoftheproject": "**Two directions emerged** from the seven explored: sticky scroll and horizontal flip cards. Both solved the visibility problem differently \u2014 and **that difference became the central design debate of the project**.",
  "": "The initial ideation session was run with **leadership present**. No polished decks, just sketches, **rapid concept generation**, and real time stakeholder input shaping the direction. \n\nSeven distinct layout concepts explored on paper, each addressing the same **core tension**: how do you surface five subdivision destinations without sacrificing the hero's primary job of establishing PITS's brand identity?",
  "": "**Heading \u2014 14.9%**\nThe majority of predicted attention landed on the carousel headline \u2014 but this is misleading. The heading was rotating through unrelated service announcements. Attention was captured by movement, not meaning. Users were reading a Windows 10 update notice on a B2B IT company's homepage.\n\n**Primary CTA \u2014 2.4% / 0.7%**\nThe two most important action buttons on the page (Get Free Consultation and Learn More) captured a combined 3.1% of attention. Effectively invisible. A visitor motivated to convert had no clear path forward.\n",
  "": "**Contact CTA \u2014 0.3%**\nThe nav bar contact button registered near zero fixation. The highest intent action on the entire page was the least seen element.\n\n**Subdivision Logos \u2014 3.9% / 3.0% / 1.1%**\nThree subdivision logos combined for just 8% of total predicted attention \u2014 and that attention was passive. Logo recognition, not click intent.\n\n**The right half of the page \u2014 effectively dead.**\nThe entire subdivision section \u2014 three divisions, real revenue opportunities \u2014 generated less predicted engagement than the rotating carousel heading alone.\n\n",
  "": "**Goal:** Assess whether extended exposure to the hero produces meaningful comprehension \u2014 specifically around PITS's service offering and subdivision structure.\n\n**Process:** Participants viewed the original hero for a full, uninterrupted session with no time limit. Then asked: \"What does this company do?\", \"Can you name any of their services or divisions?\", and \"Who do you think this is for?\"\n\n**Results:**\n73% failure rate on subdivision recall\nAverage comprehension score: 23%\n17 of 22 described the company only as \"an IT company\" with no further detail\n2 of 22 could name more than one subdivision\n14 of 22 could not identify who the target audience was \n\n\"I saw some logos at the bottom but didn't know what they were for\"\n\"There was too much going on \u2014 I didn't know where to look\"\n\"I assumed it was for regular consumers, not businesses\"\n\n**Findings:** Extended viewing time did not meaningfully improve comprehension. The information architecture was broken at a structural level. Users weren't missing the subdivisions because they weren't looking. They were missing them because nothing on the page communicated that those logos represented distinct, clickable business lines worth exploring.\n\n",
  "": "**Goal:** Validate whether the hero communicates who Princeton IT Services is, what they offer, and where to go next \u2014 within the first 10 seconds of landing.\n\n**Process:** Showed the original hero to 12 participants for exactly 10 seconds, then closed it. Asked three questions: \"What does this company do?\", \"What services do they offer?\", and \"Where would you click first?\"\n\n**Results:**\n6 of 12 participants could not accurately describe what Princeton IT Services does\n0 of 12 recalled seeing or registering any subdivision links\n9 of 12 could not identify a clear next step or clickable element\n\n**Findings:** Zero brand recall. Zero subdivision awareness. Zero actionable next step. The hero wasn't just underperforming \u2014 it was actively failing to communicate anything meaningful at the most critical moment of the user journey.",
  "": "**Color.** Orange runs through the whole product. Most food and health apps go green \u2014 calm, healthy, safe \u2014 and green was the wrong energy for a product built around play. Orange is warmer and louder, it's appetite-forward, and it put Hungie somewhere the category wasn't.\n\n**Type.** Rounded display type for headers, plain sans for body. The display face is playful without being a kids' font \u2014 it reads fun, not cartoonish, and it never tips into arcade. The headers carry the personality and the body text stays out of the way.\n\nThe rule underneath both: loud where it's fun, quiet where you're working.",
  "": "**The research (part 1).** Algorithms are trusted and relied on less for tasks that seem subjective rather than objective, because consumers believe algorithms lack the abilities to tackle subjective tasks. This has been tested across four lab studies with 1,400+ participants and two field studies with 56,000+ (Castelo, Bos & Lehmann). \n\n**The research (part 2).**  Simple, transparent justifications more persuasive and trustworthy than abstract ones (Herlocker).\n\n**What it meant.** \"What should I eat tonight\" is the most subjective question there is. Hungie was sitting at the worst point on the curve. But perceived objectivity is changeable.\n\n**What I changed.** Every recommendation provides plain reasoning, in an orange pill. This will make a task feel more objective and trust in the algorithm goes up.",
  "": "**The research.** Giving people even a slight amount of control over an  algorithm's output made them more satisfied, more likely to believe the algorithm was intelligent/ reliable, and more likely to use it again (Dietvorst et al.). Scrutability is a distinct design aim alongside transparency and trust (Tintarev & Masthoff). \n\n**What it meant.** Letting users tell the system it's wrong builds confidence in its intelligence and creates a feeling of transparency and trust. No model gets it right every time. The question isn't whether it messes up, but how you handle it. This change also helps fine tune models.\n\n**What I changed**. Created open feedback loop. Recommendations can be corrected if inaccurate. Created a feature so Hungie asks what worked after every meal cooked. It asks about specifics like time, technique, ingredients, taste then visibly retunes. ",
  "": "**The research.** People resist AI because they perceive that algorithms fail to consider their individual circumstances (Longoni et al.). Thus, if you are able to frame an algorithm as considering personal customizations, you remove the  resistance. \n\n**What it meant.** When a system visibly uses someone's specific details, people stop assuming it can't understand them. Hungie already knew the allergies, the restrictions, the goals, the expiry dates. All of it stayed in the back end \u2014 so on screen, the recommendations looked random.\n\n**What I changed.** Two moves. Reason pills now name personal details, not just pantry math (\"fast cooking time, like you asked\u201d). And onboarding asks more personalized questions, then shows you what it learned from them.",
  "": "**The research.** People are more willing to take a machine's judgment on subjective things when the machine feels warm and expressive rather than cold (Castelo et al.).\n\n**What it meant.**  But also, warmth is exactly what people are sick of right now \u2014 the assistant that gushes, the chatbot with a first name and a stock headshot. Following the finding too literally builds the thing users are running from, the same AI everywhere.\n\n**What I changed.** The mascot is the way through. It's warm and expressive, and it's obviously a cartoon, so it never trips the fake-friend reflex. I moved it to where the AI does something: narrating or reacting with emotes while it thinks instead of a loading spinner.",
  "": "A recommendation engine answers \"what should I cook?\" \u2014 but that's a question users only ask when they've already opened the app.\n\nThe harder, more valuable question was \"what makes someone open Hungie on an ordinary Tuesday?\" That shifted the design mandate from a utility to a habit product, and it's a different discipline: you're **no longer optimizing a single interaction, you're engineering a loop that pays the user back enough to return.** ",
  "": "If the real problem was retention, the question became: what actually makes someone come back? I looked at four different motivational models, each a legitimate way to build a habit, before narrowing to the two most defensible for this audience.\n\n**Utility-first - be the most useful tool**. Win on pure convenience: faster recommendations, smarter pantry tracking, less friction than anyone else. The problem is that utility is easy to copy and easy to out-fund, and it was the exact game the other competitors were already winning. \n\n**Wellness - motivate from the inside.** Frame cooking around how it makes you feel: less stress around eating well, less body-image pressure, consistency built through personal goals rather than external pressure. This leans on intrinsic motivation, which tends to produce more durable habits, but it asks more of the user up front and rewards them more slowly.\n\n**Gamification - motivate from the outside.** Streaks, XP, and progress mechanics drawn from the behavioral-design playbook behind most sticky habit apps. This leans on extrinsic motivation \u2014 fast, proven, and immediately engaging, but with a known failure mode: for an audience already drowning in gamified apps, another streak to maintain can read as a chore instead of a hook.\n\n**Social - motivate through other people.** Make cooking something you do alongside a community: sharing meals, reacting, building status through people rather than points. Strong long-term retention and hard for a competitor to clone, but it has a cold-start problem \u2014 a social feature is only as good as the community around it, and at launch there isn't one yet.",
}